# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apartheid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] The **1820 Settlers** were several groups of British colonists who settled in the Eastern Cape of the Cape Colony under the auspices of the government of the United Kingdom in 1820.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] After the Napoleonic Wars, Britain experienced a serious unemployment problem.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] Many of the 1820 Settlers were poor and the Cape government encouraged them to settle in the Eastern Cape in an attempt to strengthen the eastern frontier against the neighbouring Xhosa peoples, and to provide a boost to the English-speaking population of South Africa.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] The settlement policy led to the establishment of Albany, South Africa, a centre of the British diaspora in Africa.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] Of the 90,000 applicants, 19,000 were approved, but only about 4000 could be transported due to financial constraints.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] Many 1820 Settlers initially arrived in the Cape in about 60 different parties between April and June 1820.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] A group of the 1820 Settlers continued on to Natal, then a part of Zululand, home of the Zulu people.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] At the time, King Shaka ruled the territory with highly trained warriors.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] Leaders of the Natal settlers requested permission from Shaka to stay on the land.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] When the king witnessed the settlers' technological advances, permission was granted in return for access to firearm technology.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] According to genealogist Shelagh O'Byrne Spencer, among 1820 Settlers who moved to Natal were "John Bailie, the founder of East London, and Charles Kestell, after whose son, the Rev.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] John Daniel Kestell of Anglo-Boer War fame, the Free State town of Kestell is named".
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] After 5 months at sea two ships arrived at the Cape of Good Hope from London via Cork, Ireland.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] Upon feasting their eyes on the promised land, about 200 settlers lay off shore at Simonstown ("Simons Bay") for a week, before being sailed back all the way to Saldanha.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] From here they were carted to Clanwilliam ("Jan Disselsvlei") and given tiny pieces of land.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] All but 5 families (Archer, Stone, et al.) were later rescued and moved to the "Eastern Cape".
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] The five remaining families, culturally isolated from the other British Settlers, had to make do and were quickly absorbed by the Dutch/Afrikaans speaking communities.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] Some of their descendants fought against the English in the Anglo Boer wars.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] They are commemorated in Grahamstown by the 1820 Settlers National Monument, which opened in 1974.
[src:apartheid/1820-settlers] A living monument, it hosts plays, musical performances and cultural events, and is supported by the 1820 Settlers Association which was founded in 1920 by Sir Walter Stanford and other descendants.
[src:apartheid/1901-in-south-africa] The following lists events that happened during **1901 in South Africa**.
